If there is no objection to the Latinity of the passage, there is certainly none to the argument. The youth is made to say ‘there was security sufficient 3 and if you don't think that there was, you will, forsooth, send just whom you please to invade my property, and you will not let me have the opportunity of protecting my own interests! This is further explained in the next chapter: ‘at erat probatio,' &e. If the security was not sufficient, Verres ought not to have taken advantage of that, and given the contract to another, the consequence of which would be the ruin of the youth, who would be obliged to pay a large sum for repairs, which he could have made at a light cost.
